pe":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce de Botetourt was born as the daughter of Sir John Botetourt and Joyce de la Zouche. She had at least 1 daughter with Adam Peshale."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1335–1365":"1335–1365","1343–1407":"1343–1407","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1347–1369":"1347–1369","1347–1387":"1347–1387","1348–1380":"1348–1380","1348–1420":"1348–1420","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1360–1407":"1360–1407","–Female":"Surnud","1340–1419":"1340–1419","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1393–1420":"1393–1420","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1318–1385":"1318–1385","1318–1372":"1318–1372","before 31 May 1347":"enne 31. maid 1347","1385":"1385","1451":"1451","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1393":"1393","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1348":"1348","1369":"1369","1347":"1347","1346":"1346","1335":"1335","1354":"1354","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1343":"1343","1365":"1365","1419":"1419","1407":"1407","1318":"1318